om recent events that they often do not regard their staff in schools to require these either. It </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">could be very soon that questions are raised about who is running our schools, in the way that other organisations who have taken over public sector responsibilities in recent years, have been found wanting.</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:260.55pt"><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The appropriateness of academy status for prima</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ry schools and what special factors apply, and what evidence there is that academy status can bring value for money either for individual primary schools or for the system as a whole.</span></li></ol></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:248.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The academy model is designed for larger schools, therefore most </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">primaries do not fit the model. Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e small number of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> schools which have converted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, do not report much change in the working of their school , they do note that many of the services they require need to be bought back from a Local Authority in order to ensu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">re that they have some backup if things go wrong. This is often provided at the expense of  those schools which remain maintained as the infrastructure is often paid for out LA top slice. Collaborative groups of school could bring value for money, but it d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oes not need </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">academisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to gain this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Many primary schools currently perceive federation without academy status to offer many of the advantages of academy status without the major complexities of changing their status</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There has been an enormous sum of m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oney spent nationally and locally in trying to oblige primary schools to become academies by a variety of means, such as bribery and coercion, this programme has resulted in only about a 10 percent success rate, with such a poor return on the investment wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">en will someone question whether this is an acceptable waste of public money?</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-